<DIV1 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>ON MY PAST LIFE.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>HOUSE and land was my paternal lot;</L>
<L>But &s;in and extravagance made me leave my cot.</L>
<L>When my fields grew in plenty of wheat and corn,</L>
<L>I like the lark hail'd the &s;prightly morn.</L>
<L>My wife's &s;ons and daughters, once the comfort of my age,</L>
<L>Has now left the world's wide bu&s;y &s;tage;</L>
<L>And I twelve years have travel'd from my native home,</L>
<L>And doom'd in &s;canty poverty to roam:</L>
<L>And now I am mi&s;erably poor and old,</L>
<L>Keen winds I've &s;uffer'd, hunger, heat and cold,</L>
<L>And &s;uff<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters"> great afflictions. I mu&s;t not repine&mdash;</L>
<L>Be not &s;eeure&mdash;your lot may be like mine.</L>
<L>I am a man of &s;orrow, grief and mi&s;ery:</L>
<L>We ne'er were born here happine&s;s for to &s;ee.</L>
<L>Was I to tell you the &s;ource of all my grief,</L>
<L>Sure you would pray for my relief.</L>
<L>Still as through life's meandering path I &s;tray,</L>
<L>Lord be the &s;weet companion of my way,</L>
<L>And bring me &s;afely to thy ble&s;t abode,</L>
<L>Of light and life, and happine&s;s in God.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB N="28" REF="047760_0027_10248CA53005BB50">
<L>Religion's &s;acred <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">,</L>
<L>Unerring points the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">,</L>
<L>Where happine&s;s for ever &s;hines,</L>
<L>With unpolluted ray.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>My fleecy flocks with wool kept me warm,</L>
<L>And cloth'd my body from the winter &s;torm.</L>
<L>My cows bags full of milk brought to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="4 letters">door,</L>
<L>And every day in plenty gave me more.</L>
<L>Bacon and beef was my daily food;</L>
<L>The Lord that gave; the Lord is good.</L>
<L>My negroes toil'd and made me bread,</L>
<L>The &s;inful crime I felt with awful dread;</L>
<L>I trampled on the mercies of my God,</L>
<L>And for my &s;ins, &s;mote me with his rod,</L>
<L>And made me my tran&s;gre&s;&s;ions for to &s;ee,</L>
<L>And by his free grace and mercy &s;et me free.</L>
</LG>
<P>[Rom. vii. 9.&mdash;For I was alive without the law once, but when the commandment came, &s;in revived, and I died.]</P>
<LG>
<L>I four years was condemned for my &s;in,</L>
<L>But I, like the dove, my Noah took me in.</L>
<L>Now I am in his ark from danger free,</L>
<L>Which will land me on eternity.</L>
<L>Six months I travel'd in dark de&s;pair,</L>
<L>The di&s;mal burden of temptation for to bear&mdash;</L>
<L>To hang my&s;elf&mdash;to cut my children's throats&mdash;</L>
<L>To drown my&s;elf&mdash;to fall out of boats&mdash;</L>
<L>To burn a wheat field&mdash;to de&s;troy man's bread&mdash;</L>
<L>Then be damn'd, with wilful cur&s;es on my head&mdash;</L>
<L>To open a mill-dam, and let the water go&mdash;</L>
<L>I might not drown my&s;elf in eternal woe.</L>
<L>I went to Philadelphia to be confin'd, that I might not kill my &s;on;</L>
<L>I felt I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">as a wretched &s;oul undone.</L>
<L>I fear'd on earth I &s;hould not long dwell,</L>
<L>But &s;ink down into a di&s;mal hell:</L>
<L>Tempted to fall headlong down into wells,</L>
<L>Terrified by the ringing of court bells.</L>
<L>I fear'd the pri&s;on and the court of men,</L>
<L>I &s;hould be condemn'd for murder and hang'd; then</L>
<L><PB N="29" REF="047760_0028_10248E2C40A62340">
I ran through &s;wamps, like a dog mad,</L>
<L>Driven with horror, my heart &s;o bad.</L>
<L>Lying in the woods, &s;atan by my &s;ide,</L>
<L>My heart full of cur&s;ed pride.</L>
<L>My wretched &s;oul, how<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">guilty and forlorn,</L>
<L>Wi&s;hing I was never born,</L>
<L>To &s;uffer &s;uch dreadful &s;cenes of woe,</L>
<L>I did not know what to do or where to go.</L>
<L>The rainy &s;torms and thunders in the &s;kies,</L>
<L>The lightning I fear'd would burn out my eyes,</L>
<L>And &s;end my &s;oul into burning fire,</L>
<L>To be tormented, never to expire.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Now for a &s;ong of grateful prai&s;e,</L>
<L>With all his &s;aints I'll join to rai&s;e.</L>
<L>Who pluck'd me from the jaws of hell?</L>
<L>My JESUS has done all things well.</L>
</LG>
<P>[Prov. XXV. 14.&mdash;Who&s;o boa&s;teth him&s;elf of a fal&s;e gift, is like wind and clouds without rain.]</P>
<LG>
<L>When infidelity abounds, I employ my pen,</L>
<L>To &s;et forth the characters of deluded men.</L>
<L>The infidelian PAINE, the Dei&s;t man,</L>
<L>Who has written again&s;t the Go&s;pel Plan;</L>
<L>The Arians and Socinians, that de&s;pi&s;e the Son of God,</L>
<L>Set at naught a Redeemer's blood;</L>
<L>Tru&s;ting on a righteou&s;ne&s;s of their own,</L>
<L>Rejecting the &s;acrifice who did atone.</L>
</LG>
<P>[The wicked &s;hall be turned into hell, and all nations that forget God. P&s;. xvi. 17.]</P>
<LG>
<L>The Murrianites in no hell believe,</L>
<L>But all a full redemption &s;hall receive.</L>
<L>WINCHESTER the Univer&s;alian has left the go&s;pel way,</L>
<L>Preaching fal&s;e to lead the blind a&s;tray.</L>
<L>WORTHLARIAN and COXTERIAN has left the Bapti&s;t cla&s;s,</L>
<L>And gone the way of Balaam that &s;mote his a&s;s;</L>
<L>Believing all that &s;inn'd by Adam's fall,</L>
<L>Will be redeem'd from hell's mi&s;ery and thrall.</L>
</LG>
<P>[Ezek. xiii. 14.&mdash;O I&s;rael! thy prophets are like foxes in the de&s;arts&mdash;xxxiv. 3&mdash;Woe be to the Shep|herds that feed them&s;elves&mdash;Should not the &s;hepherds feed the flocks? Ye eat the fat, and ye cloathe you with
<PB N="30" REF="047760_0029_10248CA767E93960">the wool; ye kill them that are fed, but ye feed not the flock. The di&s;ea&s;ed ye have not &s;trengthened, neither have ye healed that which is &s;ick, neither have bound up that which was broken, neither have you brought again that which was driven away, neither have ye &s;ought that which was lo&s;t, but with force and cruelty ye have ruled them.&mdash;Song of Solomon ii. 15.&mdash; Take us the foxes, the little foxes that &s;poil the vines, for our vines have tender grapes.]</P>
<LG>
<L>You blind &s;hepherds, that de&s;troy men's &s;ouls,</L>
<L>Like tinkers of great noi&s;e to &s;top old holes.</L>
<L>Seek a pardon from the King Gibba's altar;</L>
<L>You have ri&s;en again&s;t his kingdom, mu&s;t have a halter;</L>
<L>Like Haman plotted that the Jews might die,</L>
<L>Was hung on a gallows fifty cubits high.</L>
<L>Hiram ran ve&s;&s;els in the clayey ground,</L>
<L>Your metal is filthy dro&s;s, and not the go&s;pel &s;ound;</L>
<L>It will not fit the Scripture-would,</L>
<L>Nor join together, neither being hot nor cold.</L>
<L>Don't add nor dimini&s;h from the word of God.</L>
<L>Le&s;t you feel his avenging rod.</L>
<L>You eat the fat, and don't feed the &s;heep,</L>
<L>You have no &s;eed &s;own and cannot reap.</L>
<L>Unbutton, and open your &s;leeping eyes,</L>
<L>Le&s;t you never &s;ee a God above the &s;kies:</L>
<L>There is danger, warning take,</L>
<L>E&s;cape eternal death, a burning lake.</L>
<L>I am in earne&s;t&mdash;be &s;o too&mdash;</L>
<L>I am a Gentile&mdash;you are like a harden'd Jew&mdash;</L>
<L>You &s;tarve the flock, and love the flo<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters"></L>
<L>Foxes that &s;poil the vines and kill the gee&s;e&mdash;</L>
<L>You rob hen-roo&s;ts, and kill the pigs,</L>
<L>The devil's tories, and not true whigs;</L>
<L>Serpents in a thorn hedge wor&s;e than briers,</L>
<L>The cruel Prie&s;ts of Monks and Friars,</L>
<L>Having not a true go&s;pel hope,</L>
<L>Get their commi&s;&s;ions from the Pope;</L>
<L>By doing penance, believe their &s;ins are forgiven,</L>
<L>And think they are going their way to heaven.</L>
<L>If they go down to hell in &s;in's dirt,</L>
<L>You can't put on you there a hair &s;hirt&mdash;</L>
<L><PB N="31" REF="047760_0030_10248CA9AC52E0C8">
No pardon's di&s;pens'd to rebels there&mdash;</L>
<L>No, not for any that cur&s;e and &s;wear;</L>
<L>No, not for thieves, no, not for liars;</L>
<L>No, not for Roman Prie&s;ts, nor Friars:</L>
<L>But with the rebel crew and helli&s;h band,</L>
<L>Before God, rais'd from death and hell, to &s;tand,</L>
<L>With grim horrors falling on your guilty head,</L>
